    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c9163e49_3dcaff57",
        "filename": "minijail0.c",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 469,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-06T21:44:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "seems to me this does belong in libminijail.  that\u0027s what\u0027s responsible for forking the child and managing things.  `minijail0` itself is meant as a thin CLI layer on top of the C API.  more succinctly, there is no functionality available to the CLI that isn\u0027t available to the C API.  people who use libminijail directly to sandbox processes and launch daemons should be able to also sanely set up signal forwarding.",
      "parentUuid": "76635055_202cca3b",
      "revId": "82e175283313a43a7e501c4c9f4f3ff32a9eba0b",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "caa8dbdb_b3fe4311",
        "filename": "minijail0.c",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 469,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-06T23:47:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Actually, I was just thinking about this over dinner and I don\u0027t think this belongs in libminijail. We should not be overwriting the signal handlers of the process calling minijail_run in libminijail -- that can break programs\u0027 correctness. If processes using libminijail directly want to propagate, they can do so themselves. Apologies for not mentioning this earlier.",
      "parentUuid": "c9163e49_3dcaff57",
      "revId": "82e175283313a43a7e501c4c9f4f3ff32a9eba0b",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b65e713f_b9a5f077",
        "filename": "minijail0.c",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 469,
      "author": {
        "id": 1153474
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-06T23:52:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That was my intuition, but it looks like the struct minijail has a concept of internal and external settings. I\u0027m clearing the signal flag in minijail_preenter, and the flag is only checked/handled in the parent branch after the clone. I good also just set this up before the clone",
      "parentUuid": "caa8dbdb_b3fe4311",
      "revId": "82e175283313a43a7e501c4c9f4f3ff32a9eba0b",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "66093930_e2bdc630",
        "filename": "minijail0.c",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 469,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-07T00:18:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right, but wouldn\u0027t that be the problem? When libminijail is used by a random program to launch a sandboxed helper, the \"parent\" branch is the program itself. So, in that case, we would be possibly overwriting already-defined signal handlers used by the program.\n\nMoving it before the clone also doesn\u0027t help, that would still overwrite previously existing signal handlers.\n\nI actually think that libminijail as a library should not attempt to overwrite all signal handlers of the process using that library -- a service running sandboxed helpers using libminijail might have good reasons to have specific signal handlers.\n\nI think your original intuition is correct: minijail0, as a program, has no other objective than launching and reaping a sandboxed process. As such, it should forward all signals. But we should not force other programs using libminijail to have to give up their signal handlers just to use minijail_run.",
      "parentUuid": "b65e713f_b9a5f077",
      "revId": "82e175283313a43a7e501c4c9f4f3ff32a9eba0b",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8f7c1fd3_664d94c7",
        "filename": "minijail0.c",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 469,
      "author": {
        "id": 1153474
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-07T00:21:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "No you\u0027re totally right. I still have the CLI use-case in my head.\n\nBut if they don\u0027t want their behaviour changed, can\u0027t they just set the option to not set up the handlers? We could switch _back_ to defaulting to \u0027off\u0027 (e.g. flag dont_forward_signals becomes forward_signals which defaults to off) so it\u0027s strictly opt-in.",
      "parentUuid": "66093930_e2bdc630",
      "revId": "82e175283313a43a7e501c4c9f4f3ff32a9eba0b",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
